\begin_body

\begin_layout Part
Data Processing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each data feature 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 takes value in either a infinite subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 or a finite set.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Categorical encoding
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Categorical data has values in a finite set 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\in\left\{ v_{1},v_{2},...,v_{k}\right\} $
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, and so the number of categories is 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Two cases: the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ v_{i}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is ordered (ordinal) or not (nominal).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Label encoding (ordinal)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In label encoding, each value 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{j}$
\end_inset

 is mapped to an integer:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
v_{1} & \rightarrow0,\\
v_{2} & \rightarrow1,\\
 & ...\\
v_{k} & \rightarrow k-1.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The values 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{i}$
\end_inset

 so that are ordered.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
One hot encoding
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In one hot encoding, each value 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{j}$
\end_inset

 is mapped to a standard unit vector:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
v_{1} & \rightarrow\left(1,0,...,0\right),\\
v_{2} & \rightarrow\left(0,1,...,0\right),\\
 & ...\\
v_{k} & \rightarrow\left(0,0,...,1\right).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This should create 
\begin_inset Formula $k-1$
\end_inset

 more features for each original categorical feature.
\end_layout

